## Proposed refactor for `src/Card.tsx`

The current file packs an interactive root, raw style literals, and three fixed-pixel widths into ~25 lines — each maps cleanly to one finding. Here's a refactor that fixes all three at once, tied to each charge:

```tsx
import styles from "./Card.module.css";
import { tokens } from "@/design/tokens";

type CardProps = {
  children: React.ReactNode;
  onActivate?: () => void;
};

export function Card({ children, onActivate }: CardProps) {
  const Root = onActivate ? "button" : "div";

  return (
    <Root
      type={onActivate ? "button" : undefined}
      onClick={onActivate}
      className={styles.card}
      style={{
        background: tokens.color.surface.accent,
        color: tokens.color.text.primary,
        borderColor: tokens.color.border.subtle,
        boxShadow: tokens.shadow.sm,
        outlineColor: tokens.color.focus.ring,
      }}
    >
      <div className={styles.main}>{children}</div>
      <aside className={styles.sidebar}>sidebar</aside>
    </Root>
  );
}
```

```css
/* Card.module.css */
.card {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 50rem;          /* was width: 800px */
  padding: var(--space-6);
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 15rem;
  gap: var(--space-4);
}

.main     { font-size: clamp(1rem, 0.9rem + 0.3vw, 1.125rem); } /* was 18px */
.sidebar  { font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-text-muted); }

@media (max-width: 640px) {
  .card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  .sidebar { width: 100%; }
}
```

### How each change ties to a finding

| Finding | Charge | What changed |
|---|---|---|
| `crime_00001` | **Accessible Interaction Risk** — `<div onClick>` on line 10 | Element switches to `<button type="button">` whenever `onActivate` is passed. A real button gets focus, keyboard activation (Enter/Space), and screen-reader semantics for free — no `role`/`tabIndex`/`onKeyDown` workaround needed. If the card isn't actually interactive, the caller omits `onActivate` and we render a plain `<div>` instead of leaking a fake click handler. |
| `crime_00002` | **Design Token Escape** — 9 raw color/shadow values on lines 10/24/27 | All hex/rgb literals (`#ff00aa`, `#0a0a0a`, `#cccccc`, `#1a73e8`, `rgb(0,0,0)`, `#333333`, `#666666`) are replaced with `tokens.color.*` / `tokens.shadow.*` references, and CSS-module rules use `var(--color-*)` / `var(--space-*)` / `var(--text-*)`. Future agents extending this file copy token names forward instead of forking the palette. |
| `crime_00003` | **Responsive Fragility** — `width: 800px` (line 12), `width: 720px` and `fontSize: 18px` (line 24), no `@media` | Fixed `width: 800` becomes `width: 100%` + `max-width: 50rem`. The inner `720px` column disappears — the layout uses `grid-template-columns: 1fr 15rem` so the main column flexes. `fontSize: 18` becomes `clamp(1rem, 0.9rem + 0.3vw, 1.125rem)`. A `@media (max-width: 640px)` query collapses the grid to a single column on phones. |

### Why the structure changed too

Two side-effects of the refactor that aren't strictly required by the findings but follow from doing them properly:

- **Styles move to a CSS module.** Inline `style={{}}` is the worst place to enforce tokens — every prop is a fresh literal opportunity. Moving layout/typography to a stylesheet keeps the inline `style` block down to the few token-bound colors that genuinely vary per instance.
- **The sidebar becomes `<aside>`.** Not in the findings, but once the root is correctly a `<button>`-or-`<div>`, the nested `<div>` for "sidebar" is the obvious next semantic mismatch — cheap to fix while you're here.

If `onActivate` isn't part of the API yet, the minimal accessibility fix (and the one that matches the suggested action exactly) is to drop the `onClick` entirely — the original handler only logs, so it may be dead code.
